.TH "DOCUMENT.STARTVIEWTRANSITION" "3JS" "December 9, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Document.startViewTransition \- Document: startViewTransition() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]startViewTransition()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Document\f[R] interface starts a new same\-document (SPA) view
transition and returns a \f[CR]ViewTransition\f[R] object to represent
it.
.PP
When \f[CR]startViewTransition()\f[R] is invoked, a sequence of steps is
followed as explained in The view transition process.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
startViewTransition()
startViewTransition(updateCallback)
startViewTransition(options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]updateCallback\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An optional callback function typically invoked to update the DOM during
the SPA view transition process, which returns a \f[CR]Promise\f[R].
The callback is invoked once the API has taken a snapshot of the current
page.
When the promise returned by the callback fulfills, the view transition
begins in the next frame.
If the promise returned by the callback rejects, the transition is
abandoned.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing options to configure the view transition.
It can include the following properties:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]update\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
The same \f[CR]updateCallback\f[R] function described above.
Defaults to \f[CR]null\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]types\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An array of strings representing the types applied to the view
transition.
View transition types enable selective application of CSS styles or
JavaScript logic based on the type of transition occurring.
Defaults to an empty sequence.
.RE
.SS Return value
A \f[CR]ViewTransition\f[R] object instance.
.SH EXAMPLES
See View transition API > Examples for a list of full examples.
.SS Basic usage
In this same\-document view transition, we check if the browser supports
view transitions.
If there\(cqs no support, we set the background color using a fallback
method which is applied immediately.
Otherwise, we can safely call \f[CR]document.startViewTransition()\f[R]
with animation rules that we define in CSS.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]main\f[R]>
  <\f[B]section\f[R]></\f[B]section\f[R]>
  <\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqchange\-color\(dq>Change color</\f[B]button\f[R]>
</\f[B]main\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
We are setting the \f[CR]animation\-duration\f[R] to 2 seconds using the
\f[CR]::view\-transition\-group\f[R] pseudo\-element.
.IP
.EX
html {
  \-\-bg: indigo;
}
main {
  \f[B]display\f[R]: flex;
  \f[B]flex\-direction\f[R]: column;
  \f[B]gap\f[R]: 5px;
}
section {
  \f[B]background\-color\f[R]: var(\-\-bg);
  \f[B]height\f[R]: 60px;
  \f[B]border\-radius\f[R]: 5px;
}
\f[BI]::view\-transition\-group(\f[R]root\f[BI])\f[R] {
  \f[B]animation\-duration\f[R]: 2s;
}
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] colors = [\(dqdarkred\(dq, \(dqdarkslateblue\(dq, \(dqdarkgreen\(dq];
\f[B]const\f[R] colBlock = document.querySelector(\(dqsection\(dq);
\f[B]let\f[R] count = 0;
\f[B]const\f[R] updateColor = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  colBlock.style = \(ga\-\-bg: ${colors[count]}\(ga;
  count = count !== colors.length \- 1 ? ++count : 0;
};
\f[B]const\f[R] changeColor = () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Fallback for browsers that don\(aqt support View Transitions:\f[R]
  \f[B]if\f[R] (!document.startViewTransition) {
    updateColor();
    \f[B]return\f[R];
  }

  \f[I]// With View Transitions:\f[R]
  \f[B]const\f[R] transition = document.startViewTransition(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    updateColor();
  });
};
\f[B]const\f[R] changeColorButton = document.querySelector(\(dq#change\-color\(dq);
changeColorButton.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, changeColor);
changeColorButton.addEventListener(\(dqkeypress\(dq, changeColor);
.EE
.PP
If view transitions are supported, clicking the button will transition
the color from one to another over 2 seconds.
Otherwise, the background color is set using a fallback method, without
any animation.
